2026-04-16 12:12:02 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['power supply module green LED', 'power supply module green-LED series resistor'] hypothesis_explanation='The replaced battery now provides 12 V and both PSU output cables have good continuity (≈0.1 Ω) to the battery terminals, so the supply to the rest of the system should be correct. Yet the PSU green indicator LED is off and measures only 0.012 V across its anode–cathode, which is far below a normal forward voltage (~2 V). This indicates that the LED branch is effectively shorted or otherwise failed such that almost no voltage is dropped across the LED. The most likely fault is a failed (shorted) green LED, a short across its terminals, or a mis‑connected/failed series resistor in that branch. Replacing/repairing the green LED and its series resistor inside the power supply module should restore the PSU status indication; the rest of the circuit appears supplied correctly and other remaining faults, if any, can be checked afterward.'
